HEADWORD: Inhere
<hw>In*here"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Inhered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inhering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>inhaerere</ets>; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>haerere</ets> to stick, hang. See
<er>Hesitate</er>.]</ety> <def>To be inherent; to stick (<xex>in</xex>);
to be fixed in or permanently incorporated with something; to cleave
(<xex>to</xex>); to belong, as attributes or qualities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They do but <qex>inhere</qex> in the subject that supports
them.</q> <rj><qau>Digby.</qau></rj></p>

<p><ent>Inherency</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Inherence</ent>⟦br⟧
